{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1783727781,"nonce":"qMJKobf1wCWE16LEb2WSuAVKn4w=","message":"Fixed in PR #99 (squash `ba34336`).\n\nThe runtime query render path is now fallible: a recursive CTE arm carrying its own `ORDER BY`/`LIMIT`/`OFFSET` targeting SQLite (no valid rendering — SQLite's grammar forbids the parenthesized arm scoping requires) surfaces the reject as a **returned error** from `execute`/`fetch`/`prepare` and from the new fallible `try_to_sql()`, instead of panicking. `to_sql()` stays infallible and is documented to panic on such a dynamic shape. The shape remains valid on PostgreSQL and MySQL (parenthesized arm) — the reject is not broadened.\n\nImplementation:\n- New `Backend::render_error(io::Error) -\u003e Self::Error`; the param collectors map the CTE-prefix reject through it, and the prepared renderers capture it into the existing `PreparedSql` error channel (surfaced via `into_parts()`). Also fixed the `*-select`/`*-using` params collectors, which had swallowed the reject with `.ok()` (caught by codex — `SqliteInsertSelect::collect_params()` had returned `Ok` for an unrenderable source).\n- A `Render` variant added to each backend `Error` (`io::Error`; a `String` on the test backend).\n- `try_to_sql()` added to every query object; execute/fetch/prepare route SQL through the fallible path.\n- Reworded the `RecursiveCteDefinition` SQLite-limitation note (returns an error now, not a panic).\n\nLocal codex clean after 2 rounds; full verify green (fmt/clippy/build/test/compile_fail); required CI (test + MSRV) green.","files":null}]}